<!--
    ClickHouse Keeper connection config — mounted on every ClickHouse data node.

    This file tells each ClickHouse node where to find the Keeper cluster. Despite the
    XML element being named <zookeeper>, it works with ClickHouse Keeper (the native
    replacement) as well as with Apache ZooKeeper — the protocol is compatible.

    ClickHouse uses this connection to:
      - Register and track replicated data parts (ReplicatedMergeTree coordination)
      - Manage the per-replica replication queue
      - Execute distributed DDL (ON CLUSTER statements)
      - Elect merge leaders across replicas

    SINGLE KEEPER NODE (current — local dev)
    ═════════════════════════════════════════
    One <node> entry pointing at the single keeper container on port 9181.
    If this container is unreachable, data nodes can still serve reads but cannot
    commit new inserts or run replicated DDL until the connection is restored.

    MULTI-NODE KEEPER (production / HA)
    ════════════════════════════════════
    List ALL Keeper nodes here. ClickHouse will try them in order and automatically
    failover to the next one if the current leader is unreachable. You only need to
    reach a majority of Keeper nodes for the cluster to be operational.

    Example for a 3-node Keeper cluster:

        <zookeeper>
            <node>
                <host>clickhouse-keeper-1</host>
                <port>9181</port>
            </node>
            <node>
                <host>clickhouse-keeper-2</host>
                <port>9181</port>
            </node>
            <node>
                <host>clickhouse-keeper-3</host>
                <port>9181</port>
            </node>
        </zookeeper>

    All three Keeper hostnames must also be listed in each keeper node's
    <raft_configuration> block (see conf/keeper/keeper_config.xml).
-->
<clickhouse>
    <zookeeper>
        <node>
            <host>clickhouse-keeper</host>
            <port>9181</port>
        </node>
    </zookeeper>
</clickhouse>
